Mongolia to Get New Aid Worth $250 Million 
A group of countries and international organizations pledged here today
to provide Mongolia with some 250 million U.S. dollars of new aid next
year to support the country's bid to create a market economy.
The decision was made at the 6th Mongolian Assistance Group Meeting,
which ended in Tokyo today.
Co-sponsored by the Japanese government and the World Bank, the meeting
was attended by 20 countries and six international organizations.
The participants also agreed to hold the next session within 18 months
in Ulan Bator, the capital of Mongolia.
